QUESTION: What is the cooling off period before a strike?
================================================================================

[Qwen2.5-7B] (sem_sim=0.750, lat=5.36s)
The cooling-off period before a strike is 15 days according to Articles 278(d)(f), unless the termination of union officers constitutes union busting, then the 15-day cooling-off period does not apply. Under those circumstances, the union can act immediately.

[LLaMA-3.1-8B] (sem_sim=0.784, lat=4.54s)
The cooling-off period before a strike is 15 days according to Art. 278(d), except when the existence of the union is threatened due to the dismissal of union officials, then immediate action can be taken.

[Gemma-2-9B] (sem_sim=0.797, lat=10.69s)
Under Article 278,  "The notice of strike...must include information regarding the proposed date of commencement of the strike..."   

It further states "...in the absence of a duly certified or recognized bargaining agent, the notice of strike may be filed by any legitimate labor organization in behalf of its members".

However, no specific mention of a cooling-off period duration is given within these excerpts.


