QUESTION: Can an employer reduce wages?
================================================================================

[Qwen2.5-7B] (sem_sim=0.729, lat=9.07s)
An employer may not unilaterally reduce wages without proper authorization or justification. According to Art. 118, it would constitute retaliatory measures if done after an employee files a complaint or testifies in related proceedings. Additionally, reducing wages indirectly through actions like limiting their disposal per Art. 112 is prohibited. Therefore, wage reductions must adhere strictly to lawful provisions and agreements between parties.

Art. 118 and Art. 112 provide protections regarding unauthorized reduction of wages.

[LLaMA-3.1-8B] (sem_sim=0.687, lat=7.79s)
No, it would be unlawful for an employer to reduce wages without just cause. However, there may be instances like closure of establishments or reduction of personnel wherein employers can provide alternative forms of payment according to Art. 299 does mention termination however I am assuming you meant wage reductions so referring back to source ART. 118 states retaliatory measures including refusal to pay full wages thus implying they must remain intact unless justified.

[Gemma-2-9B] (sem_sim=0.740, lat=7.97s)
Under Article 118, it shall be unlawful for an employer to...refuse to pay or reduce the wages ...or discriminate against any employee who has filed any complaint or instituted any proceeding under this Title....


